1 Implement a parallel mean filter for image smoothing

Start by loading the required packages for this assignment.

require("parallel")
## Loading required package: parallel
require("png")
## Loading required package: png

Create the mean filter function.

filtermean = function(matrix, k) {
  n = ncol(matrix)
  m = nrow(matrix)
  padded = matrix
  # pad sides
  for(p in 1:k) {
    padded = cbind(padded, rep(0, m))
    padded = cbind(rep(0, m), padded)
  }
  # pad top and bottom
  for(p in 1:k) {
    padded = rbind(padded, rep(0, (n + 2*k)))
    padded = rbind(rep(0, (n + 2*k)), padded)
  }
  filtered = padded
  for(row in (k+1):(m+k)) {
    for(col in (k+1):(n+k)) {
      window = padded[(row-k):(row+k), (col-k):(col+k)] 
      filtered[row, col] = mean(window)
    }
  }
  filtered = filtered[(k+1):(m+k), (k+1):(n+k)] # remove padding
  return(filtered)
}

Apply the ‘filtermean’ function to the “Wheatfield with Crows” painting by Vincent Van Gogh using k=1.

vg = readPNG("Van_Gogh.png")

# divide the image into red, green, and blue color channels.
red.vg = vg[,,1]
green.vg = vg[,,2]
blue.vg = vg[,,3]

a = mclapply(X=list(red.vg, green.vg, blue.vg), FUN=filtermean, mc.cores=3, k=1) # parallel

v = array(c(a[[1]], a[[2]], a[[3]]), dim = c(nrow(a[[1]]), ncol(a[[1]]), 3))

writePNG(v, "fliou_1.png")

2 Detect edges

Create the filter function using standard deviation instead of mean in order to detect the edges of a desired image. This function highlights the pixels with the top 10% of standard deviations in the image.

filtersd = function(matrix, k) {
  n = ncol(matrix)
  m = nrow(matrix)
  padded = matrix
  #pad sides
  for(p in 1:k) {
    padded = cbind(padded, rep(0, m))
    padded = cbind(rep(0, m), padded)
  }
  #pad top and bottom
  for(p in 1:k) {
    padded = rbind(padded, rep(0, (n + 2*k)))
    padded = rbind(rep(0, (n + 2*k)), padded)
  }
  filtered = padded
  for(row in (k+1):(m+k)) {
    for(col in (k+1):(n+k)) {
      window = padded[(row-k):(row+k), (col-k):(col+k)]
      filtered[row, col] = sd(window)
    }
  }
  filtered = filtered[(k+1):(m+k), (k+1):(n+k)]
  filtered[filtered > quantile(filtered, prob=1-10/100)] = 1
  return(filtered)
}

Use the ‘filtersd’ function to detect the edges of the red color channel of the Van Gogh painting.

red.edges = filtersd(red.vg, 1)
writePNG(red.edges, "VanGoghRedEdge.png")

Resulting Image: These edges from the red channel emphasize the birds flying over the field.

Now let’s do the same thing, but this time, we’ll look at all three color channels of a bird’s eye view of Madison, WI.
